data.content:
**Yes, C# fully supports `stackalloc`'d `Span<nint>` and `Span<nuint>`.** Both compiled and ran without issues on .NET 11 (tested here). This feature has been available since C# 9 / .NET 5, when `nint`/`nuint` were introduced as first-class types.

```csharp
Span<nint> nints = stackalloc nint[4];
Span<nuint> nuints = stackalloc nuint[3];
```

Both work exactly as you'd expect — they allocate on the stack and are accessed through the `Span<T>` API just like any other unmanaged type.
